%%TITLE
The prevalence of human papillomavirus in oropharyngeal cancer is increasing regardless of sex or race, and the influence of sex and race on survival is modified by human papillomavirus tumor status.
%%ABSTRACT
The purpose of this study was to evaluate the influence of sex and race/ethnicity upon prevalence trends of human papillomavirus (HPV) in oropharyngeal cancer (OPC) and survival after OPC.This was a cohort study of patients included in the United States National Cancer Database who had been diagnosed with OPC between 2010 and 2015. Outcomes were HPV status of tumor specimens and overall survival. Sex- and race-stratified trends in HPV prevalence were estimated using generalized linear modeling. The influence of sex, race, and HPV tumor status on overall survival was compared by Kaplan-Meier method and Cox Proportional Hazards models.This analysis included 20,886 HPV-positive and 10,364 HPV-negative OPC patients. The prevalence of HPV-positive tumors was higher among men (70.6%) than women (56.3%) and increased significantly over time at a rate of 3.5% and 3.2% per year among men and women, respectively. The prevalence of HPV-positive tumors was highest among whites (70.2%), followed by Hispanics (61.3%), Asians (55.8%), and blacks (46.3%). Blacks and Hispanics experienced significantly more rapid increases in prevalence of HPV-positive tumors over time compared with whites (6.5% vs 5.6% vs 3.2% per year, respectively). In HPV-positive OPC, neither sex nor race/ethnicity was associated with survival among patients with HPV-positive OPC. In contrast, for HPV-negative OPC, risk of death was significantly higher for women versus men (adjusted hazard ratio [aHR], 1.17; 95% confidence interval [CI], 1.08-1.26) and blacks versus whites (aHR, 1.21; 95% CI, 1.10-1.33).The prevalence of HPV-positive tumors is increasing for all sex and race/ethnicity groups in the United States. Sex and race are independently associated with survival for HPV-negative but not HPV-positive OPC.
%%METHODS
Patient, tissue samples
Three hundred and ten (n = 310) consecutive cases with suspected head and neck carcinoma attending Department of Otolaryngology, Post Grad- uate Institute of Medical Education and Research (PGIMER), Chandi- garh, India from January-2013 to December-2014 were enrolled in this study after obtaining informed consent from individual patients. The study was approved by the Institutional Ethics Committee (IEC), Post Graduate Institute of Medical Education and Research (PGIMER), Chandigarh, India. Detailed clinical and epidemiological information including the patient’s age, sex, addiction habits of each patient was obtained. Emphasis was given on their addiction habits. The lifetime exposure to smoking and alcohol (Sharma et al, 2010) was measured as:
Lifetime exposure to smoking ¼ No. of Cigarettes=beedis per day
x Duration of smoking ðyearsÞ;
Lifetime exposure to alcohol ¼ No. of shots per day
x Duration of alcohol intake ðyearsÞ:
HNSCC samples were divided into four group based on site of cancer: oropharynx (back one-third of the tongue, soft palate, side and back walls of the throat and tonsils), oral cavity (front two-thirds of the tongue, gingiva, buccal mucosa, ﬂoor of the mouth, hard palate, and retromolar trigone), hypopharynx, and larynx.
Histopathological diagnosis
Detailed clinical examination of each patient was done to assess the site, size, and type of lesions. A punch biopsy was performed using the stan- dard protocol by an ENT surgeon. One part of oral biopsies was col- lected in RNA-later and immediately processed for molecular diagnosis, whereas the other half was suspended in formalin solution for histopatho- logical diagnosis. Patients having lesions with an abnormal epithelial sur- face like erythroplakia, leukoplakia, and submucosal lesions including hemangiomas, mucoceles, papilloma, aphthous ulcers, melanoplakia, and ﬁbromas were excluded. Those with no evidence of malignancy, non- Hodgkin lymphoma, and other non-representative cases were excluded.
HPV and HPV-16 detection by conventional PCR
Genomic DNA was isolated from the frozen tissue of premalignant and malignant group using standard proteinase K digestion method and puri- ﬁed by phenol–chloroform extraction. HPV was detected in DNA sam- ples isolated from biopsies by using two sets of consensus primers: MY09-MY11 primers and Gp5+/Gp6+ primers targeting the HPV L1 gene. HPV-16 was detected using HPV-16 E6-speciﬁc primers (Karlsen et al, 1996) (See Data S1, Figure S1).
HPV-16 viral load 63
HPV-16 viral load was determined by quantitative real-time PCR (Flores- Munguia et al, 2004). Approximately, 50 ng of each DNA sample was subjected to real-time PCR for HPV-16 viral load analysis (See Data S2, Figure S2.1).
Viral copies per cell (VC) was calculated by the following formula:
VC ¼ ðCalculated copies of E6=Calculated copies of b-globinÞ* 2:
Based on viral load analysis, the median value of 100 copies/1000 cells was used to classify the HPV-16 positive samples as high viral load (>100 copies/1000 cells) and low viral load (<100 copies/1000 cells) (Seaman et al, 2010). Integration status was determined using E6/E2 ratio and accordingly the samples were classiﬁed as episomal (E2/E6 > 0.8), mixed (both the episomal and integrated, E2/E6 < 0.8), and integrated (E2/E6 < 0.4) (Roberts et al, 2008).
HPV-16 E7 mRNA Expression
Total RNA was extracted with mirVanaTM RNA isolation kit (Thermo Fisher Scientiﬁc, MA, USA). All samples were treated with DNase I, Ampliﬁcation Grade (AMPD1-1KT; Sigma-Aldrich, USA) before cDNA synthesis with Verso cDNA synthesis Kit (Thermo Fisher Scientiﬁc, MA, USA). The relative expression of HPV-16 E7 mRNA was measured by using the real-time PCR (RT-PCR) (Data S2, Figure S2.2).
Immuno-histochemical Analysis
HPV-16 positive samples were further examined by immuno-histochemis- try for expression of three HPV-speciﬁc pathway proteins: nuclear p16, nuclear and cytoplasmic p53, and nuclear pRB. Anti-p16 (sc-9968; Santa Cruz Biotechnology, Inc., Texas, USA), anti-p53 (sc-6243, Santa Cruz Biotechnology, Inc., Texas, USA), and anti-pRb (sc-73598, Santa Cruz Biotechnology, Inc., Texas, USA) were used for immuno-histochemical staining. The sections were visualized using high sensitivity peroxidase- DAB system (Dako REALTM ENVISIONTM Detection System, Glostrup, Denmark).
Immuno-staining for all antibodies was quantiﬁed by counting the cells exhibiting positive staining with a given antibody and the intensity of staining (See Data S3, Figure S3).
Statistical Analysis
Statistical analysis was performed using SPSS with the exact tests pack- age (IBM, Armonk, NY, USA). For all analyses, a P value of 0.05 or less was considered statistically signiﬁcant. Patient variables were com- pared using the Fisher exact test.
